Theresa May's Stage
London — The task facing Britain's new prime minister, Theresa May, is a daunting one: to implement the electorate's vote to "leave the European Union" — or more accurately, the voters of England and Wales — and to manage the far-reaching consequences of this task.
This challenge is greater than any faced by her predecessors in recent years.
But she may have the capacity to accomplish this task.
No one should underestimate May.
Like German Chancellor Merkel, who has already demonstrated courage in a series of crises, Theresa May has all the tools needed to accomplish the task in her hands.
She is smart and resilient, and has no patience for nonsense.
She has a strong sense of public service and equally strong values.
She is not bound by any ideology, is very good at taking control, and acts within the boundaries she sets herself to ensure familiarity with the issues she handles.
Theresa May has won most of the battles she has been involved in, and is merciless towards those who have treated her with underhanded methods.
But she has few enemies within the party and is very popular among ordinary members.
This is a powerful combination — she needs to make full use of it to lead Britain's Brexit process.
There is no doubt that the Brexit process has already begun.
Even though Scotland and Northern Ireland voted to remain in the EU, May has repeatedly stated that the Brexit referendum cannot be reversed.
She has repeatedly stated "Brexit means Brexit," and her ministers under her also agree with her view.
But May has yet to give a precise definition of Brexit.
This task is very difficult to accomplish.
Imagine someone telling you, "Breakfast is breakfast," and then starting to prepare food for you.
It is hard to clearly know what you will actually be eating.
An Ulster fry from Northern Ireland — eggs, bacon, sausage, black pudding, potatoes, soda bread, and fried tomatoes — with a cup of tea?
Coffee and pastries?
Depending on your environment and personal preferences, you might feel very differently about various possible combinations.
The same applies to Brexit.
Some may primarily focus on preventing EU labor from entering Britain.
Others may be more concerned about securing access to the single market.
But unlike breakfast, Britain cannot order every item on the menu.
The reality often overlooked by Brexit supporters is that the EU will not give Britain benefits for free.
This is not because EU leaders want to win favor or punish Britain for rejecting the EU (such inflammatory rhetoric sometimes spreads widely, for example, when Britain's new foreign secretary Boris Johnson called it "Hitler-style imperialism").
On the contrary, we Britons often forget that everyone — including the EU and all its member states — has political or commercial interests they swear to protect.
For May, the core challenge in the coming months will be to determine what Britain's goals should be, based on reality, after the tough negotiations on its relationship with the EU (and its relationship with the world in the area of trade) begin?
Given the scope of the agenda (I can think of at least six major topics that will need separate negotiations), the negotiation process may take several years to complete.
(By the time the negotiations are completed, my 11-year-old granddaughter may already be starting university!
) We must clarify our priorities to prevent the negotiations from taking even longer.
The goal is certainly to achieve a balance between allowing British goods and services (especially financial services) to enter other European countries and restricting the movement of EU citizens into the UK.
The more negotiators gain in one area, the greater the concessions they will need to make in other areas.
May needs to make full use of the knowledge, skills, and political capital she possesses to ensure the reasonableness of the negotiation deal.
But even if she succeeds in achieving her goal, she will still find that the dissatisfied people are not just a part of them — this outcome is inevitable — but all of them.
This will exacerbate another major challenge facing May's government: narrowing the growing divide in British society exposed by Brexit.
Blue-collar workers in northern and central England were the main force behind the Brexit referendum, and they have always been alienated from political leaders, left behind by globalization, and marginalized by what is supposed to be globalization's proxy — the European Union.
The metropolitan areas of England — especially London — may have benefited greatly from globalization, but they have received no benefits at all.
Many members of the blue-collar working class, due to a lack of confidence in the Labour Party led by left-wing leader Jeremy Corbyn, ultimately became victims of the populist promises of the Brexit movement.
"We will reverse globalization," they said.
"We will get rid of immigrants who drive down wages and transfer hundreds of millions of pounds, which would otherwise go to the EU, into public services."
They promised that Brexit would return Britain to a safer and more prosperous past.
Brexit supporters cannot truly deliver on these promises.
Globalization cannot be reversed, nor can immigration from the European Union be cut off.
Any such move would only destroy British businesses.
Even if economic downturns lead to a decrease in immigration, workers who voted for Brexit may still be disheartened to find that low-paying jobs remain low-paying and public service pressures remain heavy.
This is unlikely to lead to an increase in social cohesion.
The Brexit referendum has already triggered an uncontrollable populist emotional storm.
Just as Donald Trump was unable to improve the situation of working-class American voters, Brexit, no matter how the situation may seem, cannot bring any benefits to those who chose it.
Despite its many advantages, such challenges may still be beyond May's ability to overcome.
